Scuba Diving Grand Cayman - Oro Verde<br/><br/>The &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Oro Verde shipwreck&lt;/a&gt; in Grand Cayman has been a favorite site for divers since she was sunk on May 31, 1980 by the Cayman government.  The vessel a &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery-image%2FOro-Verde%2FG0000oIFpDg4SWto%2FI0000I55grfjXZj0%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery-image/Oro-Verde/G0000oIFpDg4SWto/I0000I55grfjXZj0&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;131-foot 692-ton freighte&lt;/a&gt;r lies in about 50 feet of water just off Grand Cayman's famous Seven Mile Beach.  The wreck has deteriorated a lot since her reefing, mainly as a result of several hurricanes that have hit the island in the last 30 years. &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FOro-Verde%2FG0000oIFpDg4SWto%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Oro-Verde/G0000oIFpDg4SWto/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The debris field&lt;/a&gt; today is scattered over a wide area with only the &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery-image%2FOro-Verde%2FG0000oIFpDg4SWto%2FI0000I.h2e7kuj2s%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery-image/Oro-Verde/G0000oIFpDg4SWto/I0000I.h2e7kuj2s&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Oro Verde&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;bow section &lt;/a&gt; still intact.
<br /><br />You can read about the history and background of the &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fblog.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fdive-site-reviews-and-listings%2Fdive-sites%2Fscuba-diving-grand-cayman-oro-verde-shipwreck%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://blog.stevenwsmeltzer.com/dive-site-reviews-and-listings/dive-sites/scuba-diving-grand-cayman-oro-verde-shipwreck/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Oro Verde&lt;/a&gt; on my &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fblog.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://blog.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;blog&lt;/a&gt; and view the complete &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FOro-Verde%2FG0000oIFpDg4SWto%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Oro-Verde/G0000oIFpDg4SWto&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;underwater photo gallery&lt;/a&gt; on my website.
<br />&lt;h3&gt;The Dive&lt;/h3&gt;
<br />The &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FOro-Verde%2FG0000oIFpDg4SWto%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Oro-Verde/G0000oIFpDg4SWto/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;shipwreck&lt;/a&gt; and surrounding reefs are home to a variety of marine life including, &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FCaribbean-Fish%2FG0000l7UPDDuOGA0%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Caribbean-Fish/G0000l7UPDDuOGA0/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;fish&lt;/a&gt;, turtles, custaceans and corals, making this one of the most popular shallow &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;dives in Grand Cayman&lt;/a&gt;, often frequented after a deeper wall dive or on a night dive.  Though it was in pristine condition when it was sunk and lying on her starboard in the sand next door to a patch of reef, the &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;wreck's&lt;/a&gt; finer details have since given way to the force of time; passing hurricanes have broken, rolled and scattered the vessel across a wide debris field closer to the reef. Still, the&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Oro Verde&lt;/a&gt;remains a great example of a thriving&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery-image%2FOro-Verde%2FG0000oIFpDg4SWto%2FI0000egxo.Zip33U%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery-image/Oro-Verde/G0000oIFpDg4SWto/I0000egxo.Zip33U&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt; artificial reef.&lt;/a&gt; The buoy is attached to the bow section which is the only remaining intact part of the wreck.  There are no longer any ways to penetrate the wreck but you can look into the bow section through a couple of port holes.  &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FShipwrecks%2FG0000OtMyTETA74I%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Shipwrecks/G0000OtMyTETA74I/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The debris field&lt;/a&gt; flows primarily from the bow section to the north along several coral fingers.  The diver can choose to spend all or part of the dive on the wreck and part of the dive on the reef. There is a wide variety of reef fish such as &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FCaribbean-Fish%2FG0000l7UPDDuOGA0%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Caribbean-Fish/G0000l7UPDDuOGA0/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Parrotfish, Sergeant Majors, Angelfish, Silversides&lt;/a&gt; (seasonally), schoolmasters, large groupers and moray eels as well as crustaceans such as the arrow crab and rough file clam
<br /><br />This is a very worthwhile dive  and I especially like it as a night dive for the variety of marine species that are present.  &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fblog.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fdive-site-reviews-and-listings%2Fdive-sites%2Fscuba-diving-grand-cayman-oro-verde-shipwreck%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://blog.stevenwsmeltzer.com/dive-site-reviews-and-listings/dive-sites/scuba-diving-grand-cayman-oro-verde-shipwreck/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The Oro Verde&lt;/a&gt; lies about 100 yards off shore so advanced divers in good physical condition could reach it as a shore dive but with the long swim and requisite dive flags and floats due to offshore boat traffic, why bother? All of the local dive operators will be happy to take you to the Oro Verde as your second half of a two tank west side boat dive, an afternoon dive or on a &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery-image%2FMoray-Eels%2FG0000lAjRNX9s.XM%2FI00005Ta8Y0MP5DE%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery-image/Moray-Eels/G0000lAjRNX9s.XM/I00005Ta8Y0MP5DE&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;night dive&lt;/a&gt;.  I would urge you to dive the wreck whether it is the first time or it you have dove on the wreck before.  The site is constantly changing and the marine species always make for an interesting dive.
<br /><br />Check out images of other wrecks in Grand Cayman the &lt;a title=&quot;Doc Poulson Gallery&quot; href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FDoc-Paulson%2FG0000TGXE_MiE3nA%2F%26quot%3B%26gt%3BDoc"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Doc-Paulson/G0000TGXE_MiE3nA/&quot;&gt;Doc</a> Poulson&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a title=&quot;USS Kittiwake Galery&quot; href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FKittiwake-Grand-Cayman%2FG0000JtpXOPWAQac%2F%26quot%3B%26gt%3BUSS"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Kittiwake-Grand-Cayman/G0000JtpXOPWAQac/&quot;&gt;USS</a> Kittiwake&lt;/a&gt;

Scuba Diving Maui - Black Rock<br/><br/>Black rock or Sheraton Reef rates average for &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;scuba diving&lt;/a&gt; Maui during the day, but is a bit above average when compared to other shore diving locations in the Kaanapali area. I do rate it a bit better as a night dive site. However, when&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt; Scuba Diving Maui &lt;/a&gt;near Kaanapali, I would recommend Mala Pier as a much better shore dive either during the day or at night if transportation is not a problem.
<br />&lt;ul&gt;
<br />  &lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ffff00;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Access - Moderate difficulty to reach the site; Easy entry into the water&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
<br />	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ffff00;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Depth to 45ft&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
<br />	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ffff00;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Visibility - average to good&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
<br />	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ffff00;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Current - moderate to quite strong&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
<br />	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ffff00;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Marine Species variety - Moderate&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
<br />	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: #ffff00;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reef health - Moderate&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
<br />&lt;/ul&gt;
<br />The dive at Black Rock is quite shallow allowing for a dive that can run 60 minutes or more depending upon your air consumption. The current can be quite strong after you pass the rocky point for which the dive site receives its name, so inexperienced divers should only dive this site with a local guide. The dive shop at the Sheraton, In 2 Scuba, is ok but the staff that I have used tends to be younger and inexperienced and I tend to brief them on how I will dive the site. So if you are an experienced diver, there is no reason you cannot do this dive on your own, but you will have to bring your own equipment or rent gear and bring it in.
<br /><br />You enter the site in the beach area of the Sheraton Maui Resort and Spa. You can access the beach whether you are staying at the hotel or not, but getting your gear to the beach can be an adventure. You have to park in a parking garage near the front of the hotel and then haul your gear a good distance to the beach probably about 200 meters The local dive operator on the beach, &quot;In 2 Scuba&quot;, does not &quot;rent tanks&quot; or at least they have not in the past, so you need to rent these off site, I rent typically at Lahaina Divers, and/or sign up for a guided dive from the onsite dive shop. I have been able to get the valet to sometimes take my equipment down to the beach but that usually involves a nice tip. There is a place to rinse your gear by the Scuba Diving shack and ample places to gear up prior to the dive.
<br /><br />Once you are geared up, the entry is quite easy, the beach is a little steep just before entering the water, but the waves are typically very small due to the protection from the cliff. During the day, there tends to be a number of snorkelers above you on this site and you need to be careful on the entry and exit.
<br /><br />The dive is quite easy if the current is not too strong. You swim out about 20 to 30 meters from the beach and thensubmerge and swim out and around the rocky promontory, from which you can watch &quot;cliff diving&quot; during the day. If there is a current you will feel it immediately as you go around the point and it will get stronger for about the next 50 meters or so and then taper off a bit. The variety of&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery%2FScuba-Diving-Underwater-Photography%2FG0000BWCcQG1I0II%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery/Scuba-Diving-Underwater-Photography/G0000BWCcQG1I0II/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt; marine life&lt;/a&gt; is reasonable and you will almost always see several sea turtles once you round the point. This is a favorite site for many large turtles to come in for a nap. Typically you can see a large number of eels including &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery-image%2FMoray-Eels%2FG0000lAjRNX9s.XM%2FI0000pkbDx6dCFoo%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery-image/Moray-Eels/G0000lAjRNX9s.XM/I0000pkbDx6dCFoo&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Yellow Margin Eels&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery-image%2FMoray-Eels%2FG0000lAjRNX9s.XM%2FI0000gVHxHBipFCk%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery-image/Moray-Eels/G0000lAjRNX9s.XM/I0000gVHxHBipFCk&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Undulated Moray Eels&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery-image%2FMoray-Eels%2FG0000lAjRNX9s.XM%2FI0000n5XqIatwp_U%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery-image/Moray-Eels/G0000lAjRNX9s.XM/I0000n5XqIatwp_U&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Whitemouth Moray Eels&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery-image%2FMoray-Eels%2FG0000lAjRNX9s.XM%2FI0000jE1X53Vtjuo%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery-image/Moray-Eels/G0000lAjRNX9s.XM/I0000jE1X53Vtjuo&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Zebra Moray Eels&lt;/a&gt; and others. As you head away from the beach the cliff will be to your right and open ocean on your left. The cliff has a number of crevices as you round the point that are well worth exploring as you will sometimes find a variety of shrimp, such as the rare &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery-image%2FCrustaceans-and-Echinoderms%2FG0000OLcModvF7w4%2FI0000IZs3Rh3LCys%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery-image/Crustaceans-and-Echinoderms/G0000OLcModvF7w4/I0000IZs3Rh3LCys&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Candy Cane Shrimp&lt;/a&gt;, and various types of cleaners. There also tend to be a number of Goatfish just away from the wall along with variouspuffer fishes, &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery-image%2FHawaiian-Fish-Pictures%2FG0000nEnP4ApIAak%2FI0000OandS1Heqp8%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery-image/Hawaiian-Fish-Pictures/G0000nEnP4ApIAak/I0000OandS1Heqp8&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;butterflyfishes&lt;/a&gt; and parrotfishes staying fairly close to the cliff.. The water tends to have a good bit of sand and other debris which makes photography a bit challenging so remember to keep your strobes pointed away from your subject to eliminate backscatter and shoot as close as possible. However, if the current is not too strong you can get reasonable visibility and clarity. As you round the point make sure you look out away from the cliff about 10 meters to 25 meters, you will sometimes find one or more rays staying virtually motionless in the current and feeding. You have to approach them very, very slowly and close to the bottom or you will cause them to move away. If they are present stop and watch them a bit before you begin the approach. I had a dive in 2011 in the spring where three Manta Rays were hovering and feeding and another diver sprinted to get a closer look and needless to say that was the last that we saw of them. So again go slow, and approach very cautiously and you will tend to see more.  You will be diving against the current so continue swimming out beside the cliff until you reach about 1500 PSI and then simply turn around and follow the same path back in.  If for some reason you do run short on air this site is very forgiving and you can simply surface and then swim back around to where you entered, just make sure you stay wide of the point.  The wave action here can be quite strong and the rocks can do a lot of damage if you were to get pushed up against them.
<br /><br />Overall a fun dive and I usually make it once or twice when I am in &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Maui&lt;/a&gt; and usually at night.
<br /><br />&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Maui&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The pool is open&lt;/a&gt;...

Scuba Diving Grand Cayman - Roundabout<br/><br/>Overall Rating 3.9
<br />&lt;a title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FScuba-Diving-Grand-Cayman%2FG0000DLsGbyx7U5k%2F%26quot%3B%26gt%3BRoundabout%26lt%3B%2Fa%26gt"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Scuba-Diving-Grand-Cayman/G0000DLsGbyx7U5k/&quot;&gt;Roundabout&lt;/a&gt</a>; can be either a first/deep dive or many times I have been on this site as a second /shallow dive site on the north wall in Grand Cayman.  It can be quite good as it has a very good variety of soft and hard corals and normally has an abundant variety of marine species.  The downside of the site is that it can also be a bit turbid after hard rains due to the close proximity to the cuts in the reef from the North Sound to the Caribbean Sea that allow &quot;runoff&quot; to cloud the dive site.
<br /><br />Access - Relatively easy; boat only;  Typically fairly easy entry into the water but rougher seas can make this a bit of an adventure on re-boarding the boat which is typical to any north wall dive in &lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.stevenwsmeltzer.com%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.stevenwsmeltzer.com/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Grand Cayman&lt;/a&gt;; 
<br />Depth to 60+ft (on top of the wall); 
<br />Visibility - average to excellent; 
<br />Current - moderate to quite strong; 
<br />&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery%2FScuba-Diving-Underwater-Photography%2FG0000BWCcQG1I0II%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery/Scuba-Diving-Underwater-Photography/G0000BWCcQG1I0II/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Marine Species variety&lt;/a&gt; - Good; 
<br />Reef health - Good to very good; 
<br /><br />This scuba diving typically has sea turtles, such as the Hawksbill, or Green Sea Turtle.   You can distinguish the &lt;a title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FSea-Turtles%2FG0000sfq3MVhBuZM%2F%26quot%3B%26gt%3BHawksbill"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Sea-Turtles/G0000sfq3MVhBuZM/&quot;&gt;Hawksbill</a> &lt;/a&gt;from the Green Sea Turtle by looking at its head and the plates between its eyes.  If you see 2 sets of plates - 2 between the eyes and 2 just about its beak/bill, then it is a Hawksbill.  The Green Sea Turtle just has two plates between its eyes.  You will also see a variety of parrotfishes, such as the &lt;a title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FCaribbean-Fish%2FG0000l7UPDDuOGA0%2F%26quot%3B%26gt%3BPrinces"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Caribbean-Fish/G0000l7UPDDuOGA0/&quot;&gt;Princes</a> Parrotfish&lt;/a&gt; or Stoplight Parrotfish, a variety of of small oval type fishes such as the Barred Hamlet, and if you look closely in the crevices within the coral reef you will find a variety of &lt;a href=&quot;&quot; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;crustaceans&lt;/a&gt; and juvenile fish species.
<br /><br />This is usually a very relaxing and interesting dive, since it is done on top of the wall you have plenty of time to explore.  You will occasionally see a nurse shark or ray cruising the sand channels between the reef and there are always a good number of lobsters about, you just have to go slowly and look diligently.  I was trying to take a shot of an Eagle Ray that was &quot;flying around the site&quot; when I turned around and this &lt;a title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FMoray-Eels%2FG0000lAjRNX9s.XM%2F%26quot%3B%26gt%3BGreen"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Moray-Eels/G0000lAjRNX9s.XM/&quot;&gt;Green</a> Moray&lt;/a&gt; had just about jumped into my lap.  It just shows that it is a good idea to continually look around or have your dive buddy let you know when something interesting happens to swim nearby.  Just don't use pulling your hair as the signal, but that is a story for another time.... Typically you can do this dive as a dive buddy and your only responsibility is to monitor your air and your computer to make sure you don't get into &quot;deco&quot; time.  You can also follow the dive master around to see what they can help find.  Either way, I like to cruise the&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com%2Fgallery%2FScuba-Diving-Grand-Cayman%2FG0000DLsGbyx7U5k%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.photoshelter.com/gallery/Scuba-Diving-Grand-Cayman/G0000DLsGbyx7U5k/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt; top of the wall&lt;/a&gt; for a bit and look out into the &quot;blue&quot; to see if anything interesting is around.  I then usually swim very slowly over the top of the reef and enjoy the variety of&lt;a href=&quot;<a href="http://en.pan.netcom/go/out/url=http%3A%2F%2Fstevenwsmeltzer.com%2Fgallery%2FCoral-Reefs%2FG00007HdqcXifCa4%2F%26quot"target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://stevenwsmeltzer.com/gallery/Coral-Reefs/G00007HdqcXifCa4/&quot</a>; title=&quot;Scuba Diving Grand Cayman&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt; soft corals&lt;/a&gt; that are on this site and also look for smaller marine animals that might make a good shot.
